data.content:
These tests are already in good shape — factory method, injected clock, clear AAA structure, focused assertions. A few things to tighten up:

**1. Repeated magic strings** — `"user@example.com"` and `"admin"` appear in 4 tests. Extract constants so a signature change is a one-line fix:

```csharp
private const string DefaultEmail = "user@example.com";
private const string DefaultRole = "admin";
```

**2. Clock leaks in the assertion** — `GenerateToken_ValidUser` asserts against `DateTime.UtcNow` instead of the injected `FakeClock`. If the test ever runs near a boundary or the clock semantics change, this breaks silently. Assert against the same clock the service uses:

```csharp
var clock = new FakeClock(DateTimeOffset.UtcNow);
var service = new TokenService(clock, new InMemoryTokenStore());

var token = service.GenerateToken(email, role);

Assert.IsTrue(token.ExpiresAt > clock.UtcNow);
```

This means `CreateTokenService` should expose or return the clock — e.g., return a tuple or a small helper record.

**3. Minor: `CreateTokenService` ternary is redundant** — both branches do the same thing when `clockOffset` is `null` (adds `default(TimeSpan)` which is zero). Simplify:

```csharp
var clock = new FakeClock(DateTimeOffset.UtcNow + (clockOffset ?? TimeSpan.Zero));
```

Everything else — parameterized `DataRow` tests, idempotency coverage, exception testing, DI seams — is solid and will age well.
